{
  "texts": [
    "The learned value function V (x) serves as an approximation to the true optimal cost-to-go function V * (x), which is defined as:V * (x t) = min {u k } ∞ k=t ∞ k=t γ k-t r(x k, u k),(21)subject to the system dynamics x k+1 = f (x k, u k).",
    "Since the exact function V * (x) is generally unknown or intractable in high-dimensional, nonlinear systems, ADP approximates it using a parameterized function:V (x; θ) = N i=1 θ i ϕ i (x) = Φ(x) ⊤ θ,(22)where ϕ i (x) are chosen basis functions (e.g., radial basis functions, polynomials, or neural network activations), θ i are trainable weights, and Φ(x) is the feature vector.",
    "Alternatively, V (x) may be implemented using a neural network denoted by N θ (x), where θ represents the learnable parameters of the network.",
    "The immediate cost function r(x k, u k) quantifies the penalty associated with the current state and control input.",
    "It is typically designed to penalize deviations from desired operating conditions and to discourage excessive control effort."
  ]
}